<div id="review_953749787" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/953749787" />
    <a title="Sanjay Gautam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10179929-sanjay-gautam"><img alt="Sanjay Gautam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627894093p2/10179929.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/953749787?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sanjay Gautam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sanjay Gautam" href="/user/show/10179929-sanjay-gautam">Sanjay Gautam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Laymen interested in science and maths.</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer953749787" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer865017304364031957"><i>There was a young fellow from Trinity<br/>Who took √∞ (square root of infinity)<br/>But the number of digits <br/>Gave him the fidgets;<br/>He dropped Math and took up Divinity.</i><br/><br/><br/><b> <u>There&apos;s magic in these pages. </u></b><br/><br/>Gamow, one of the greatest physicists of 20th century, whose passion for the maths and science is communicated in this book, whether explaining the wonders of infinite series, or how to locate a hidden pirate&apos;s treasure chest using imaginary numbers. The book explains how mathematics and science really work, in</span>
  <span id="freeText865017304364031957" style="display:none"><i>There was a young fellow from Trinity<br />Who took √∞ (square root of infinity)<br />But the number of digits <br />Gave him the fidgets;<br />He dropped Math and took up Divinity.</i><br /><br /><br /><b> <u>There's magic in these pages. </u></b><br /><br />Gamow, one of the greatest physicists of 20th century, whose passion for the maths and science is communicated in this book, whether explaining the wonders of infinite series, or how to locate a hidden pirate's treasure chest using imaginary numbers. The book explains how mathematics and science really work, in a language that a layman can understand. Some chapters of the book are simple enough to be understood by a child, whereas others require some concentration and study to be completely understood. And he doesn't shy away from hardcore mathematics, if needed.<br /><br />HIGHLY RECOMMENDED!<br /><br /></span>
