  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4427940926" />
    <a title="Jade" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108909236-jade"><img alt="Jade" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593736495p2/108909236.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4427940926?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jade" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jade" href="/user/show/108909236-jade">Jade</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108909236-jade?shelf=science">science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4427940926" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6837292879774656335">great book that covers general science that was relevant to the world at the time of writing (this revised edition was published in 1960). it’s mostly about physics, covering concepts as small as the atom and as large as the universe; math, biology, and chemistry are sprinkled in where applicable. each complex topic is made digestible through Gamow’s careful (and at times witty) writing, and aided by illustrations that added to my enjoyability and understanding of the text.<br/><br/>being written so long </span>
  <span id="freeText6837292879774656335" style="display:none">great book that covers general science that was relevant to the world at the time of writing (this revised edition was published in 1960). it’s mostly about physics, covering concepts as small as the atom and as large as the universe; math, biology, and chemistry are sprinkled in where applicable. each complex topic is made digestible through Gamow’s careful (and at times witty) writing, and aided by illustrations that added to my enjoyability and understanding of the text.<br /><br />being written so long ago, it’s inevitable that some “facts” stated in the book have been disproven, or questions asked at the time have now been answered. however, from my knowledge of topics discussed in the book, almost all of it still holds up and the reading experience remains interesting. all in all, Gamow provided a wealth of information that left me with new questions about the way our universe works, as any good science book of this type should.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6837292879774656335" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
