    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3896863826" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3896863826" />
    <a title="Geoffrey Weiss" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/79558137-geoffrey-weiss"><img alt="Geoffrey Weiss" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541103454p2/79558137.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3896863826?book_show_action=true">Mar 18, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Geoffrey Weiss" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Geoffrey Weiss" href="/user/show/79558137-geoffrey-weiss">Geoffrey Weiss</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3896863826" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6700387249212206039">Published in 1947, this book provides a fascinating look backward to a time when the physical sciences were on the verge of explosive growth in knowledge. The author, George Gamow, an astrophysicist at George Washington University, offers perspectives that stretch the imagination (e.g., there are numerous infinities; probabilities, entropy and the second law of thermodynamics). But the attractive aspect of the book is the manner in which it provides a lens on the physicochemical landscape of the</span>
  <span id="freeText6700387249212206039" style="display:none">Published in 1947, this book provides a fascinating look backward to a time when the physical sciences were on the verge of explosive growth in knowledge. The author, George Gamow, an astrophysicist at George Washington University, offers perspectives that stretch the imagination (e.g., there are numerous infinities; probabilities, entropy and the second law of thermodynamics). But the attractive aspect of the book is the manner in which it provides a lens on the physicochemical landscape of the mid-Twentieth Century: before DNA was discovered, chromosomal mutations were regarded a simple variation on isomeric chemistry; the centers of galaxies were simply dense aggregations of stars before the concept of dark energy and black holes; the concept of the heavier elements arising from dying stars had not yet been considered. The book is an easy read, filled with amusing prose and entertaining drawings by the author.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6700387249212206039" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


